Package com.github.tommyettinger.ds

Class NumberedSet<T>

java.lang.Object
com.github.tommyettinger.ds.NumberedSet<T>
Type Parameters:
T - the type of items; should implement Object.equals(Object) and Object.hashCode()
All Implemented Interfaces:
Arrangeable, Ordered<T>, Iterable<T>, Collection<T>, Set<T>
public class NumberedSet<T> extends Object implements Set<T>, Ordered<T>
An Ordered Set of T items where the indexOf(Object) operation runs in constant time, but any removal from the middle of the order runs in linear time. If you primarily append to a Set with add(Object), this will perform like ObjectIntOrderedMap, since it's backed internally by one of those Maps; indexOf() delegates to the map's ObjectIntMap.get(Object) method. This has to do some bookkeeping to make sure the index for each item is stored as the value for the key matching the item in the map. That bookkeeping will fail if you use the Iterator.remove() method on this class' iterator; you can correct the indices with renumber(), or renumber(int) if you know the first incorrect index.

    • renumber

      public void renumber()
      Reassigns all index values to match order(). This should be called if you have removed any items using Iterator.remove() from this NumberedSet, since the iterator's remove() method doesn't update the numbering on its own. Use this method if you don't know the first incorrect index, or renumber(int) if you do.

    • renumber

      public void renumber​(int start)
      Reassigns the index values for each index starting with start, and going to the end. This should be called if you have removed any items using Iterator.remove() from this NumberedSet, since the iterator's remove() method doesn't update the numbering on its own. Use renumber() if you don't know the first incorrect index, or this method if you do.
      Parameters:
      start - the first index to reassign.
